You're probably thinking so what at that but to me it's a big step.  I never jump at home, I always prefer to jump away at a ready built course or under instruction, in the past I've just found myself to over think it a too much, worry about strides and make the little confidence I did have disappear. 

Our lessons have been going well lately and I felt Carlos needed to do a little something different to give him a break away from flatwork but knowing I needed to run through my tests for tomorrow's dressage I figured letting him have a pop over a few jumps afterwards might just do that!

He was awful on the flat, he went near, past or around every jump like it was a giant hole trying to swallow him up.  Once I'd run through my two tests and felt I knew them I carried on cantering around the corner and set him up for a cross pole I set out.  I felt him wobble but when I put my leg on her locked on.  We did it a couple times on both rein before attempting the plank, he hates them.  But he did the same, a bit of a wobble but with leg on he set himself up for it.  However in mid air decided he still didn't like it and looked down at the cone and did some weird movement, trying to get away from it but I just laughed so much at him.

I did it again and the jump was much better.  Thought I'd push my luck and try the plank on the plain end, he flew it so ended with a good pat and a long cool off. 

Now I'm thinking it may not have been a good idea to jump before dressage as he's most likely to break into canter when he's not meant to in the tests tomorrow. Haha oh well. 

